\f1\b0 \
\
       Clay County was carved from the wilderness between 1818 and 1824. The\
       first permanent settlers arrived after the conclusion of the War of 1812\
        Indian conflicts (~1815\'961818). The county was formally organized in\
       December 1824.\
\
       By the time Stephen and Polly likely arrived (probably ~1820\'961825, after\
        their 1817 Kentucky marriage and the birth of son William in 1814 \'97\
       note: if William was born 1814, Stephen may have been in the region\
       earlier, possibly in Lawrence County before Clay County was organized),\
       the area was raw frontier.\
\
       
\f0\b Farming:
\f1\b0  Settlers grew corn, wheat, and vegetables and raised hogs and\
       cattle. Hogs were turned loose in the timber bottoms in autumn to fatten\
        on acorn and hickory mast \'97 a self-feeding system requiring minimal\
       investment. Corn was the staple crop. Fencing rules were established by\
       1834. Labor was extremely scarce; families did all their own work.\
\
       
\f0\b Markets:
\f1\b0  The great challenge of Clay County was its inland location. In\
       the 1820s and into the 1840s, farmers 
\f0\b built
\f1\b0  
\f0\b flatboats
\f1\b0  
\f0\b on
\f1\b0  
\f0\b the
\f1\b0  
\f0\b Little
\f1\b0 \
       
\f0\b Wabash
\f1\b0  
\f0\b River
\f1\b0 , loading bags of grain and barrels of pickled pork, and\
       floated them down the Little Wabash to the Wabash River, then to the\
       Ohio, then down the Mississippi all the way to 
\f0\b New
\f1\b0  
\f0\b Orleans
\f1\b0  \'97 a round\
       trip of months. This was the primary cash economy. By the 1840s this\
       became more regularized.\
\
       
\f0\b Land:
\f1\b0  The first generation of Clay County settlers entered land from the\
        federal government at $1.25/acre minimum (set by the Land Act of 1820).\
        An 80-acre entry cost $100 \'97 substantial but achievable. Many settlers\
       entered 40\'9680 acres initially. The county seat moved from Maysville to\
       Louisville in 1841.\
\
       
\f0\b Communities:
\f1\b0  Tiny and scattered. Churches (often Methodist or Baptist,\
       the dominant faiths of Scots-Irish Appalachian migrants) doubled as\
       community centers. Schools were one-room log cabins charging ~$2.50 per\
       pupil per quarter. The region attracted settlers primarily from Indiana,\
        Kentucky, and Tennessee \'97 a mix reflecting the Appalachian/Upper South\
       migration pattern.\
\
       
\f0\b Stephen's
\f1\b0  
\f0\b likely
\f1\b0  
\f0\b occupation:
\f1\b0  Subsistence farmer with a hog-and-corn\
       operation, probably with some livestock on open range, and likely\
       participating in the flatboat trade at least occasionally. His household\
        in 1840 shows adult children (one or two sons aged 20\'9630), meaning he\
       would have had considerable help in the fields by the late 1830s.\
\
