       include Stephen \'97 but that profile only lists 4 children and is\
       acknowledged as incomplete. A Revolutionary War veteran with a 20+ year\
       marriage would likely have more children than are documented.\
       2. The Heinegg "Free African Americans" database lists a 
\f0\b "COY
\f1\b0  
\f0\b FAMILY"
\f1\b0  in\
        Amherst County with an 
\f0\b Anthony
\f1\b0  
\f0\b Coy
\f1\b0  (head of household, 3 "other free"\
       persons,\'a01810) \'97 suggesting that the Coy family in Amherst may have been\
        classified as free people of color. Heinegg's research documents\
       families of mixed African, European, and sometimes Native American\
       ancestry. If the Amherst Coys were of this classification, it would\
       explain why Anthony and Stephen don't appear in standard white household\
        counts and why their ancestry is harder to trace. However, this needs\
       caution \'97 the Anthony Coy in the "other free" list could be a different\
       family, and the Coy family documented by Heinegg (Sarah Coy, Charles\
       Coy) is rooted in 
\f0\b Powhatan
\f1\b0  
\f0\b County
\f1\b0 , not Amherst. The evidence is\
       suggestive but not conclusive.\
